<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-681-211  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 681 211.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Publishing Systems  Nov 26 1990 v20 n6 p6(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alfa's OS/2 port nearly complete.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>Alfa's OS/2 port nearly complete Alfa System Partner, which has received somenegative publicity as a result of losing its contract to supply software forthe EPOS system at Rheinische Post, demonstrated the positive side of itssituation.andP;  It has nearly completed porting its software to OS/2.andP;  Moreover,many of the features developed for that system have been incorporated intoAlfa's main product.andM;Alfa has largely completed porting page planning, page layout and classifiedpagination software to OS/2 and Presentation Manager.andP;  Their largest site,the Wien Courant in Austria, is claimed to be paginating automatically about80 pages of lineage and display advertising through the system on a peaknight.andM;Most system functions have been converted to standard hardware and software,with proprietary Megadata terminals phased out in favor of Nokia Alfaskopunits.andP;  The main editing terminal application and advertising booking rununder MS-DOS.andP;  Pagination uses OS/2.andP;  File servers and network control stillrequire Prime minicomputers under the Primos operating system and PrimeNetEthernet support.andM;Despite rumors to the contrary, Alfa states that it is having a good year andis making money, although it admits that the previous year was quiet.andM;Regarding the Rheinische Post situation, IBM is the main contractor andhardware supplier, as we reported from Drupa.andP;  Alfa, which stated that itwithdrew from the project for various reasons, said that similar software isin use in another major project is Zurich, where Alfa is subcontracting toMCC.andP;  Alfa said that everything is working to plan at that site.andO;</TEXT></DOC>